michael@seawest.seachange.com (Michael Burke) writes:

To offer a contrasting opinion ...

>Roll your own firewalls might be fun to create, but they have little 
>documentation and are very hard to audit. These are usually very hard to 
>confirm actual protection levels.

Just because you have a commercial firewall doesn't mean you shouldn't
audit it. I've found far too many of these that don't actually stop things
that the documentation would make you believe that they stop.

>The commercial firewall products usually offer more functions than just 
>simple firewall security. Check them all out before making a purchase.

This is true. The problem is that I've never seen a commercial product that
I didn't have to 'roll-my-own' to make it do everything I needed it to do.
A lot of them come with built-in assumptions that just don't work.

>Not all commercial firewall products are equal. Find the best and stick 
>to it (We believe that we provide the best, BTW).

And obviously, this man has something to sell.



---
The clearest matter lies in the fact that commercial firewall packages can
greatly simply the process of creating a good firewall, but they can't do
it for you.  If the person creating the firewall doesn't have the skill set
to 'roll-his-own', then they probably don't have the skill set to properly
test and ceritfy a system built with a commercial firewall.

Good software never replaces a good administrator, but it can make their
life easier.

